   \"model\": \"AHV-Holding-DEV\",\n      \"contextTokens\": 200000,\n      \"totalTokens\": 45314,\n      \"estimatedCostUsd\": 0,\n      \"status\": \"running\",\n      \"startedAt\": 1776207735553,\n      \"childSessions\": [\n        \"agent:master-orchestrator:subagent:c2d275a5-d70a-4775-a268-fecf4708f133\",\n        \"agent:planner:subagent:63bb70ce-b5f3-48d0-a236-b6cf5d8d7922\",\n        \"agent:planner:subagent:ba49ac6d-ceff-4a9d-b3b1-7b89afdd88cc\"\n      ],\n      \"systemSent\": true,\n      \"abortedLastRun\": false,\n      \"lastChannel\": \"webchat\",\n      \"transcriptPath\": \"/root/.openclaw/agents/master-orchestrator/sessions/08b84afb-eb8f-47ef-b20e-48c56d1d9819.jsonl\",\n      \"messages\": [\n        {\n          \"role\": \"assistant\",\n          \"content\": [\n            {\n              \"type\": \"thinking\",\n              \"thinking\": \"Now I have both the current sessions list and the last known state from heartbeat-state.json. Let me compare:\\n\\n**Last known state (heartbeat-state.json):**\\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d`: running ✅\\n- `cron:e7885813`: done ✅\\n- `cron:6f3323ef`: running ✅\\n- `cron:53c5832a`: done ✅\\n- `main`: done ✅\\n- `telegram:direct:6053576134`: done ✅\\n- `telegram:group:-5163901258`: running ✅\\n\\n**Current state (00:10 UTC):**\\n\\n\\nThe QLHV monitor and DTLX Monitor are both still running as expected, while the Agent Status to Lead cron has finished, the daily briefing cron has completed normally, and the main process is done.\\n\\nLooking at the comparison between the last state and now, the `cron:e7885813` process that was running in the previous check has ended, and a new instance has spawned. All the monitoring crons are cycling normally through their 5-minute intervals, with no failures or blockers detected.\\n\\nNow I'm checking whether `cron:e7885813` ended abnormally or normally by looking at its session history—it shows as \\\"running\\\" but was aborted at `1776211405874`, which is about 23:43 UTC, just under 2 minutes into execution. I'm seeing that `cron:e7885813` ended due to an abort around 23:43 UTC, but the parent cron session (`cron:ed2d0b5d`) that spawned child sessions is still running normally. The comparison to the last known state shows these are expected lifecycle events—the old instance ended, a new one spawned, and both the Daily Briefing and agent status completed their normal cycles. Looking at the timestamps more carefully, the parent cron at 00:10 is still running while its child finished around 23:43, which suggests either a manual abort or a timeout—the child had very low token counts (just 2 messages total), so it likely hit a timeout limit and stopped. The parent cron itself has 3 child sessions still listed as active, so it's not stuck in a loop.\\n\\nComparing to the baseline state from earlier, the main difference is that `cron:e7885813` transitioned from \\\"running\\\" to \\\"done\\\" (or possibly \\\"aborted\\\"), which appears to be a normal completion rather than a failure—the new instance spawned in the next cycle confirms the cron is functioning as expected.\\n\\nLooking at the heartbeat-state.json, the session is marked as running but the actual session history shows it aborted after just 11 seconds with only one message sent, indicating it was a brief timeout during the night silence period that doesn't warrant an alert. The cron itself appears to be cycling normally as designed. The child session `cron:e7885813` aborted due to timeout, but since a new instance spawned shortly after, this is expected behavior—the cron is cycling normally rather than failing. There's also a zombie `cron:ac986a8d` that ran for about 10 hours before going silent, which matches a previously reported issue. Comparing against the last state, only the aborted child represents a change, but this is within normal operational parameters.\\n\\nThe pipeline health is good with all three crons running, though I'm noticing a discrepancy between the session meta